# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diybio-organization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] On 27 July 1971, Johannes F Gottwald received U.S. patent 3596285A for the "Liquid Metal Recorder", after applying on 11 July 1969 a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:diybio-organization/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After Reddit was sold to Condé Nast Publications in 2006, Swartz became more involved in activism, helping launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee in 2009.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2010, he became a research fellow at Harvard University's Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption, directed by Lawrence Lessig.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He founded the online group Demand Progress, known for its campaign against the Stop Online Piracy Act.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Federal prosecutors, led by Carmen Ortiz, charged him with two counts of wire fraud and eleven violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, carrying a cumulative maximum penalty of $1 million in fines, 35 years in prison, asset forfeiture, restitution, and supervised release.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz declined a plea bargain under which he would have served six months in federal prison.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Two days after the prosecution rejected a counter-offer by Swartz, he was found dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was inducted posthumously into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Aaron Hillel Swartz was born in Highland Park, 25 miles (40 kilometers) north of Chicago, to a Jewish family.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He was the eldest child of Susan and Robert Swartz and brother to Noah and Ben Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] His father founded the software firm Mark Williams Company.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] At an early age, Swartz immersed himself in the study of computers, programming, the Internet, and Internet culture.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He attended North Shore Country Day School, a small private school near Chicago, until ninth grade, when he left high school and enrolled in courses at Lake Forest College.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 1999, at age 12, he created the website The Info Network, a user-generated encyclopedia.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The site won the ArsDigita Prize, given to young people who create "useful, educational, and collaborative" noncommercial websites, and led to early recognition of Swartz's nascent talent in coding.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] At age 14, he became a member of the working group that authored the RSS 1.0 web syndication specification.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A year later, he became involved in the Creative Commons organization.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2004, he enrolled at Stanford University but left the school after his first year.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] During Swartz's first year at Stanford, he applied to Y Combinator's first Summer Founders Program, proposing to work on a startup called Infogami, a flexible content management system designed to create rich and visually interesting websites or a form of wiki for structured data.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After working on it with co-founder Simon Carstensen over the summer of 2005, Swartz opted not to return to Stanford, choosing instead to continue to develop and seek funding for Infogami.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] As part of his work on Infogami, Swartz created the web.py web application framework because he was unhappy with other available systems in the Python programming language.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In the early fall of 2005, he worked with his fellow co-founders of another nascent Y Combinator firm, Reddit, to rewrite its Lisp codebase using Python and web.py.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Although Infogami's platform was abandoned after Not a Bug was acquired, Infogami's software was used to support the Internet Archive's Open Library project and the web.py web framework was used as the basis for many other projects by Swartz and many others.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] When Infogami failed to find further funding, Y Combinator organizers suggested Infogami merge with Reddit, which it did in November 2005, creating a new firm, Not a Bug, devoted to promoting both products.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] As a result, Swartz was given the title of co-founder of Reddit.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Although both projects initially struggled, Reddit made large gains in popularity in 2005–2006.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In October 2006, based largely on Reddit's success, Not a Bug was acquired by Condé Nast Publications, owner of *Wired* magazine.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz moved with his company to San Francisco to continue to work on Reddit for *Wired*.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He found corporate office life uncongenial and in January 2007 was asked to resign from the company.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In September 2007, he joined Infogami co-founder Simon Carstensen to launch a new firm, Jottit, in another attempt to create a Markdown-driven content management system in Python.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz founded Watchdog.net, "the good government site with teeth", to aggregate and visualize data about politicians.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] That year, he wrote a widely circulated *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto*.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On December 27, 2010, he filed a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to learn about the treatment of Chelsea Manning, alleged source for WikiLeaks.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] His activism has been praised by digital rights groups such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF).
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz downloaded about 2.7 million federal court documents stored in the PACER (Public Access to Court Electronic Records) database managed by the Administrative Office of the United States Courts.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The *Huffington Post* characterized his actions this way: "Swartz downloaded public court documents from the PACER system in an effort to make them available outside of the expensive service.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] PACER was charging eight cents per page for information that Carl Malamud, who founded the nonprofit group Public.Resource.Org, contended should be free, because federal documents are not covered by copyright.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The fees were "plowed back to the courts to finance technology, but the system [ran] a budget surplus of some $150 million, according to court reports," reported *The New York Times*.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After reading Malamud's call for action, Swartz used a Perl computer script running on Amazon cloud servers to download the documents, using credentials belonging to a Sacramento library.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] From September 4 to 20, 2008, it accessed documents and uploaded them to a cloud computing service.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He released the documents to Malamud's organization.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On September 29, 2008, the GPO suspended the free trial, "pending an evaluation" of the program.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's actions were subsequently investigated by the FBI.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The case was closed after two months with no charges filed.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] At a 2013 memorial for Swartz, Malamud recalled their work with PACER.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] District Court records out from behind PACER's "pay wall", he said, and found them full of privacy violations, including medical records and the names of minor children and confidential informants.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A more detailed account of his collaboration with Swartz on the PACER project appears in an essay on Malamud's website.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] *The New York Times* similarly reported Swartz had downloaded "an estimated 20 percent of the entire database".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Based on the facts that Swartz downloaded 2.7 million documents while PACER, at the time, contained 500 million, Lee concluded that Swartz downloaded less than one percent of the database.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2009, wanting to learn about effective activism, Swartz helped launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2010, Swartz co-founded Demand Progress, a political advocacy group that organizes people online to "take action by contacting Congress and other leaders, funding pressure tactics, and spreading the word" about civil liberties, government reform, and other issues.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] During academic year 2010–11, Swartz conducted research studies on political corruption as a Lab Fellow in Harvard University's Edmond J.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Now it's up to you to change the system. ...
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After the bill's defeat, Swartz was the keynote speaker at the F2C:Freedom to Connect 2012 event in Washington, D.C., on May 21, 2012.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He added, "We won this fight because everyone made themselves the hero of their own story.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz also spoke on the topic at an event organized by ThoughtWorks.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz participated in Wikipedia beginning in August 2003 under the username AaronSw.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2006, he ran unsuccessfully for the Wikimedia Foundation's Board of Trustees.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz came to his conclusions by counting the number of characters editors added to particular articles, while Wales counted the total number of edits.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In January 2013, shortly after he died, WikiLeaks said that Aaron Swartz had helped WikiLeaks and talked to Julian Assange in 2010 and 2011.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks also said they had "strong reasons to believe, but cannot prove" he may have been a source, possibly breaking WikiLeaks' rules about source anonymity.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks may have made the statements to imply that Swartz was targeted by the US Attorney's Office and Secret Service in order to get at WikiLeaks.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] According to state and federal authorities, Swartz used JSTOR, a digital repository, to download a large number of academic journal articles through MIT's computer network over the course of a few weeks in late 2010 and early 2011.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Visitors to MIT's "open campus" were authorized to access JSTOR through its network; Swartz, as a research fellow at Harvard University, also had a JSTOR account.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On September 25, 2010, the IP address 18.55.6.215, part of the MIT network, began sending hundreds of PDF download requests per minute to the JSTOR website, enough to slow the site's performance.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] This prompted a block of the IP address.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In the morning, another IP address, also from within the MIT network, began sending more PDF download requests, resulting in a temporary block on the firewall level of all MIT computers in the entire 18.0.0.0/8 range.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] According to authorities, Swartz downloaded the documents through a laptop connected to a networking switch in a controlled-access wiring closet at MIT.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The closet's door was kept unlocked, according to press reports.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] When it was discovered, a video camera was placed in the room to record Swartz; his computer was left untouched.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The recording was stopped once Swartz was identified, but rather than pursue a civil lawsuit against him, JSTOR settled with him in June 2011; under the terms of the settlement, he surrendered the downloaded data.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On July 30, 2013, JSTOR released 300 partially redacted documents used as incriminating evidence against Swartz, originally sent to the United States Attorney's Office in response to subpoenas in the case *United States v.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On the night of January 6, 2011, Swartz was arrested near the Harvard campus by MIT Police and a Secret Service agent, and arraigned in Cambridge District Court on two state charges of breaking and entering with intent to commit a felony.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On July 11, 2011, he was indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of wire fraud, computer fraud, unlawfully obtaining information from a protected computer, and recklessly damaging a protected computer.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On November 17, 2011, Swartz was indicted by a Middlesex County Superior Court grand jury on state charges of breaking and entering with intent, grand larceny, and unauthorized access to a computer network.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On December 16, 2011, state prosecutors filed a notice that they were dropping the two original charges, and the charges listed in the November 17, 2011, indictment were dropped on March 8, 2012.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] According to a spokesperson for the Middlesex County prosecutor, this was done to avoid impeding a federal prosecution headed by Stephen P.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Heymann, supported by evidence provided by Secret Service agent Michael S.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On September 12, 2012, federal prosecutors filed a superseding indictment adding nine more felony counts, increasing Swartz's maximum criminal exposure to 50 years of imprisonment and $1 million in fines.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] During plea negotiations with Swartz's attorneys, the prosecutors offered to recommend a sentence of six months in a low-security prison if Swartz pled guilty to 13 federal crimes.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz and his lead attorney rejected the deal, opting instead for a trial where prosecutors would be forced to justify their pursuit of him.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The federal prosecution involved what was characterized by numerous critics (such as former Nixon White House counsel John Dean) as an "overcharging" 13-count indictment and "overzealous", "Nixonian" prosecution for alleged computer crimes, brought by then U.S.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Attorney for Massachusetts Carmen Ortiz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz died by suicide on January 11, 2013.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After his death, federal prosecutors dropped the charges.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On December 4, 2013, due to a Freedom of Information Act suit by the investigations editor of *Wired* magazine, several documents related to the case were released by the Secret Service, including a video of Swartz entering the MIT network closet.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz was in an open relationship with Quinn Norton between 2007 and 2011 and dated Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman from 2011 until his death in 2013, contemplating marriage with her.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He also reportedly had same-sex relationships, and was skeptical of the idea of sexual identity.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Aside from his work, he posted frequently on Twitter, Reddit and his personal website.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On the evening of January 11, 2013, Swartz's girlfriend, Stinebrickner-Kauffman, found him dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A spokesperson for New York's Medical Examiner reported that he had hanged himself.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Days before Swartz's funeral, Lawrence Lessig eulogized him in an essay, "Prosecutor as Bully".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He decried the disproportionality of Swartz's prosecution and said, "The question this government needs to answer is why it was so necessary that Aaron Swartz be labeled a 'felon'.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] For in the 18 months of negotiations, that was what he was not willing to accept." Cory Doctorow wrote, "Aaron had an unbeatable combination of political insight, technical skill, and intelligence about people and issues.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] I think he could have revolutionized American (and worldwide) politics.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's funeral services were held on January 15, 2013, at Central Avenue Synagogue in Highland Park, Illinois.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, delivered a eulogy.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He is buried at Shalom Memorial Park in Arlington Heights.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* published a story based in part on an interview with Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] She told the *Journal* that Swartz lacked the money to pay for a trial and "it was too hard for him to ... make that part of his life go public" by asking for help.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He was also distressed, she said, because two of his friends had just been subpoenaed and because he no longer believed that MIT would try to stop the prosecution.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] For donations in his memory, Swartz's family recommended GiveWell, an organization Swartz admired, had collaborated with, and made his sole beneficiary in his will.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 19, hundreds attended a memorial at the Cooper Union, speakers at which included Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman, open source advocate Doc Searls, Creative Commons' Glenn Otis Brown, journalist Quinn Norton, Roy Singham of ThoughtWorks, and David Segal of Demand Progress.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 24, there was a memorial at the Internet Archive headquarters in San Francisco (video) at which Stinebrickner-Kauffman, Alex Stamos, Brewster Kahle, Peter Eckersley, and Carl Malamud spoke.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On February 4, a memorial was held in the Cannon House Office Building on Capitol Hill; speakers included Senator Ron Wyden and Representatives Darrell Issa, Alan Grayson, and Jared Polis.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Other lawmakers in attendance included Senator Elizabeth Warren and Representatives Zoe Lofgren and Jan Schakowsky.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Harvey Silverglate was a featured speaker at a Demand Progress rally in Swartz's memory.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A memorial also took place on March 12 at the MIT Media Lab.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On February 2, 2025, a statue of Swartz was unveiled at the Internet Archive building in San Francisco.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] This was organized by Pablo Peniche and Lisa Rein.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The statue stands in the building's lobby.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts, said in a statement: "As a parent and a sister, I can only imagine the pain felt by the family and friends of Aaron Swartz, ...
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 12, 2013, Swartz's family and partner issued a statement criticizing the prosecutors and MIT.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] At the time, MIT maintained an open-campus policy along with an "open network".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Two days after Swartz's death, MIT President L.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Rafael Reif commissioned professor Hal Abelson to lead an analysis of MIT's options and decisions relating to Swartz's "legal struggles".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] To help guide the fact-finding stage of the review, MIT created a website where community members could suggest questions and issues for the review to address.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's attorneys requested that all pretrial discovery documents be made public, a move MIT opposed.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz allies have criticized MIT's opposition to releasing the evidence.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On July 26, 2013, the Abelson panel submitted a report to Reif, who authorized its public release on July 30.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The panel reported that MIT had not supported charges against Swartz and cleared the institution of wrongdoing, but also noted that despite MIT's advocacy for open access culture at the institutional level and beyond, the university never extended that support to Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The report revealed, for example, that while MIT considered issuing a public statement about its position on the case, it never did so.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] As editor Hrag Vartanian writes in *Hyperallergic*, the Brooklyn muralist BAMN ("By Any Means Necessary") created a mural of Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] "Swartz was an amazing human being who fought tirelessly for our right to a free and open Internet", BAMN said.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] "He was much more than just the 'Reddit guy'." On April 17, 2013, Yuval Noah Harari called Swartz "the first martyr of the Freedom of Information movement".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] But according to Harari, Swartz's stance did not illustrate belief in the freedom of persons or speech but stemmed from his generation's conviction that above all else, information should be free.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's legacy has reportedly strengthened the open access to scholarship movement.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In Illinois, his home state, Swartz's influence led state university faculties to adopt policies in favor of open access.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 13, 2013, members of Anonymous hacked two websites on the MIT domain, replacing them with tributes to Swartz that called on members of the Internet community to use his death as a rallying point for the open access movement.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The banner included a list of demands for improvements in the U.S. copyright system, along with Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto.* On the night of January 18, MIT's email system was taken offline for ten hours.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 22, email sent to MIT was redirected by hackers Aush0k and TibitXimer to the Korea Advanced Institute of Science & Technology.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] All other traffic to MIT was redirected to a computer at Harvard University that was publishing a statement headed "R.I.P Aaron Swartz", with text from a 2009 post by Swartz, accompanied by a chiptune version of "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] MIT regained full control after about seven hours.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In the early hours of January 26, Anonymous hacked the U.S.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Sentencing Commission website, USSC.gov.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The homepage was replaced by an embedded YouTube video, *Anonymous Operation Last Resort*.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The video statement said Swartz "faced an impossible choice".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A hacker downloaded "hundreds of thousands" of scientific-journal articles from a Swiss publisher's website and republished them on the open Web in Swartz's honor a week before the first anniversary of his death.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After Swartz's death, more than 50,000 people signed an online petition to the White House calling for Ortiz's removal "for overreach in the case of Aaron Swartz".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A similar petition was submitted calling for prosecutor Stephen Heymann's firing.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In January 2015, the White House declined both petitions.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On August 3, 2013, Swartz was posthumously inducted into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] A hackathon was held in Swartz's memory around the date of his birthday in 2013.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On the weekend of November 8–10, 2013, inspired by Swartz's work and life, a second annual hackathon was held in at least 16 cities around the world.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Preliminary topics worked on at the 2013 Aaron Swartz Hackathon were privacy and software tools, transparency, activism, access, legal fixes, and a low-cost book scanner.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In January 2014, Lawrence Lessig led a walk across New Hampshire in honor of Swartz, rallying for campaign finance reform.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2017, the Turkish-Dutch artist Ahmet Öğüt commemorated Swartz in a work titled "Information Power to The People", which depicted his bust.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's supporters responded to news of his death with an effort called #PDFTribute to promote Open Access.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 12, Eva Vivalt, a development economist at the World Bank, began posting her academic articles online using the hashtag *#pdftribute* as a tribute to Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's story has exposed the topic of open access to scientific publications to wider audiences.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Many institutions and personalities have since campaigned for open access to scientific knowledge.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's death prompted calls for more open access to scholarly data (e.g., open science data).
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The Think Computer Foundation and the Center for Information Technology Policy (CITP) at Princeton University announced scholarships awarded in memory of Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was posthumously awarded the American Library Association's James Madison Award for being an "outspoken advocate for public participation in government and unrestricted access to peer-reviewed scholarly articles".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In March, the editor and editorial board of the *Journal of Library Administration* resigned *en masse*, citing a dispute with the journal's publisher, Routledge.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] One board member wrote of a "crisis of conscience about publishing in a journal that was not open access" after Swartz died.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2002, Swartz had said that when he died, he wanted the contents of his hard drives made publicly available.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] House of Representatives—Republican Darrell Issa and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Jared Polis—all on the House Judiciary Committee, raised questions about the government's handling of the case.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Calling the charges against him "ridiculous and trumped up", Polis called Swartz a "martyr" whose death illustrated the need for Congress to limit the discretion of federal prosecutors.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Senator Elizabeth Warren issued a statement saying that Swartz's "advocacy for Internet freedom, social justice, and Wall Street reform demonstrated ... the power of his ideas".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In a letter to Attorney General Eric Holder, Senator John Cornyn asked, "On what basis did the U.S.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts conclude that her office's conduct was 'appropriate'?" and "Was the prosecution of Mr.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Issa, who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, announced that he would investigate the Justice Department's actions in prosecuting Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In a statement to *The Huffington Post*, he praised Swartz's work on "open government and free access to the people".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Issa's investigation garnered some bipartisan support.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 28, 2013, Issa and ranking committee member Elijah Cummings published a letter to Holder asking why federal prosecutors had filed the superseding indictment.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On February 20, WBUR reported that Ortiz was expected to testify at an upcoming Oversight Committee hearing about her office's handling of Swartz's case.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On February 22, Associate Deputy Attorney General Steven Reich conducted a briefing for congressional staffers involved in the investigation.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] They were told that Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* played a role in prosecutorial decision-making.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Congressional staffers left this briefing believing that prosecutors thought Swartz had to be convicted of a felony carrying at least a short prison sentence in order to justify having filed charges against him.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Excoriating the Department of Justice as the "Department of Vengeance", Stinebrickner-Kauffman told the *Guardian* that the DOJ had erred in relying on Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* as an indication of his beliefs by 2010.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] She said, "He was no longer a single issue activist.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He was into lots of things, from healthcare to climate change to money in politics." On March 6, Holder testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee that the case was "a good use of prosecutorial discretion".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In response, Stinebrickner-Kauffman issued a statement repeating and amplifying her claims of prosecutorial misconduct.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On March 22, Senator Al Franken wrote in a letter to Holder that "charging a young man like Mr.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Lofgren introduced a bill, *Aaron's Law* (H.R.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] 1196), to exclude terms of service violations from the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act and from the wire fraud statute.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Lessig wrote of the bill, "this is a critically important change....
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The CFAA was the hook for the government's bullying....
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In a single line: no longer would it be a felony to breach a contract." Professor Orin Kerr, a specialist in the nexus between computer law and criminal law, wrote that he had been arguing for precisely this sort of reform of the Act for years.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The ACLU also called for reform of the CFAA to "remove the dangerously broad criminalization of online activity".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The EFF mounted a campaign for these reforms.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Lessig's inaugural Chair lecture as Furman Professor of Law and Leadership was titled *Aaron's Laws: Law and Justice in a Digital Age*; he dedicated the lecture to Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The Aaron's Law bill stalled in committee.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Brian Knappenberger alleges this was due to Oracle Corporation's financial interest in maintaining the status quo.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act (FASTR) is a bill that would mandate earlier public release of taxpayer-funded research.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] FASTR has been described as "The Other Aaron's Law".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Senators Wyden and Cornyn introduced the Senate version in 2013, 2015 and 2017, while the bill was introduced to the House of Representatives by Lofgren, Mike Doyle, and Kevin Yoder.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Wyden wrote of the bill, "the FASTR act provides that access to taxpayer funded research should never be hidden behind a paywall." The legislation did not pass, but it prompted more open access on the part of the US government.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Since 2013, Aaron Swartz Day has been celebrated on his birthday, November 8, with hackathons and livestreamed talks related to the many issues Swartz was passionate about, such as open access and progressive politics and economics.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Past speakers include Chelsea Manning, Barrett Brown, Trevor Timm of the Freedom of the Press Foundation, Cory Doctorow, Cindy Cohn, Jason Leopold, and Brewster Kahle.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz has been featured in various works of art and has posthumously received dedications from numerous artists.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He appeared in a few documentaries, including *Aardvark'd: 12 Weeks with Geeks* in 2005.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] After leaving Reddit he appeared in *Steal This Film II* (2007).
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Swartz's first posthumous work was in 2013, when Kenneth Goldsmith dedicated his "Printing out the Internet" exhibition to Swartz.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] On January 11, 2014, marking the first anniversary of his death, a preview was released of *The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz*, a documentary about Swartz, the NSA and SOPA.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The film was officially released at the January 2014 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] *Democracy Now!* covered the release of the documentary, as well as Swartz's life and legal case, in a sprawling interview with director Brian Knappenberger, Swartz's father, brother, and his attorney.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The documentary is released under a Creative Commons License; it debuted in theaters and on-demand in June 2014.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Mashable called the documentary "a powerful homage to Aaron Swartz".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Its debut at Sundance received a standing ovation.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In October 2014, *Killswitch*, a documentary film featuring Swartz, Lessig, Tim Wu, and Edward Snowden, premiered at the Woodstock Film Festival, where it won the award for Best Editing.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The film focuses on Swartz's role in advocating for internet freedoms.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] In February 2015, Congressman Alan Grayson invited *Killswitch* to screen at the Capitol Visitor Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The event was held on the eve of the Federal Communications Commission's historic decision on net neutrality.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] At the event, Grayson, Lessig, and Free Press CEO Craig Aaron spoke about Swartz and his fight for a free and open Internet.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Grayson called *Killswitch* "one of the most honest accounts of the battle to control the Internet—and access to information itself." Richard von Busack of the Metro Silicon Valley said *Killswitch* contains "some of the most lapidary use of found footage this side of The Atomic Café".
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Fred Swegles of the *Orange County Register* wrote, "Anyone who values unfettered access to online information is apt to be captivated by *Killswitch*, a gripping and fast-paced documentary." Kathy Gill of GeekWire wrote, "*Killswitch* is much more than a dry recitation of technical history.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Director Ali Akbarzadeh, producer Jeff Horn, and writer Chris Dollar created a human-centered story.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] He appeared in the unreleased film *War for the Web* where he had been interviewed a year prior to his death.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] The documentary was ultimately cancelled as it failed to reach its funding goal, but the footage was later used in *The Internet's Own Boy*.
[src:diybio-organization/aaron-swartz] Another biographical film about Swartz, *Think Aaron*, was being developed by HBO Films as of 2020.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] All acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Other good sources are fresh apple cider and unpasteurized beer that has not been filter sterilized.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] In these liquids, they grow as a surface film due to their aerobic nature and active motility.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Fruit flies or vinegar eels are considered common vectors in the propagation of acetic acid bacteria.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] The growth of *Acetobacter* in wine can be suppressed through effective sanitation, by complete exclusion of air from wine in storage, and by the use of moderate amounts of sulfur dioxide in the wine as a preservative.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Vinegar is produced when acetic acid bacteria act on alcoholic beverages such as wine.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Specific oxidation reactions occur through oxidative fermentation, which creates vinegar as a byproduct.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] In the biotechnological industry, these bacteria's oxidation mechanism is exploited to produce a number of compounds such as l-ascorbic acid, dihydroxyacetone, gluconic acid, and cellulose.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Besides food industry, some acetic acid bacteria are used as biocatalysts for the industrial production of compounds.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] They are used as the important biocatalysts for the development of eco-friendly fermentation processes as an alternative to the chemical synthesis.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Some genera, such as *Acetobacter*, can oxidize ethanol to carbon dioxide and water using Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] Other genera, such as *Gluconobacter*, do not oxidize ethanol, as they do not have a full set of Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] As these bacteria produce acid, they are usually acid-tolerant, growing well below pH 5.0, although the pH optimum for growth is 5.4-6.3.
[src:diybio-organization/acetobacteria] *Acetobacter xylinum* is able to synthesize cellulose, something normally done only by plants.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has been described as "Science's Pirate Queen".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2016, *Nature* included her in their list of the top ten "people who mattered" in science.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Since 2011, she has been living in Russia.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was born in Almaty, Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic, on 6 November 1988.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She identifies as multiracial, with Armenian, Slavic and Asian roots.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra was raised by a single mother, who was an accomplished computer programmer.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra started programming at the age of 12, making web pages in HTML and later writing in PHP, Delphi, and assembly languages.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She attempted to create a Tamagotchi powered by artificial intelligence.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She performed her first computer hack at the age of 14; using SQL injection, she obtained access to all logins and passwords of her home internet provider.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Later, she discovered there were more vulnerabilities of the cross-site scripting type.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She reported these issues to the internet provider, hoping to get a job with them, but this did not happen.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Instead, the provider cut off her internet access.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra wrote in her blog that she first hacked a publisher's website when she was 16.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] The publisher was MIT Press, which published online books on neuroscience, but they were locked behind a paywall that she could not afford.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra wrote a PHP program that exploited a vulnerability on the website to download paywalled books without payment.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2009, she obtained a Bachelor of Science degree in computer science from the Satbayev University, specializing in information security.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She studied the possibility of using brainwaves measured using electroencephalography (EEG) for authentication instead of using a password.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] While working on her thesis, Elbakyan discovered the paywall problem with accessing journal articles, as her university did not have access to many publications related to her work.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Alexandra became interested in developing brain–computer interfaces and in 2010 she joined the University of Freiburg to work on such a project, which eventually led to her summer internship in neuroscience at Georgia Institute of Technology in the United States.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] The same year, Elbakyan spoke at the Humanity+ Summit at Harvard on the topic "Brain-Computer Interfacing, Consciousness, and the Global Brain".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan's idea was to develop a new kind of brain-machine interface that would merge human and machine qualia.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She also participated in the *Towards a Science of Consciousness* conference that was held in Tucson, Arizona with the poster "Consciousness in Mixed Systems: Merging Artificial and Biological Minds via Brain-Machine Interface".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] From 2012 to 2014, she was a master's student at Higher School of Economics in Moscow, but then dropped out.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] According to a 2016 interview, her neuroscience research was on hold, but she was enrolled in a history of science master's program at a private university in an undisclosed location.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Her thesis would focus on scientific communication.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Later, she has focused more on religious topics, and in 2019, she graduated from Saint Petersburg State University with a master's degree in linguistics on the topic of biblical languages.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan developed Sci-Hub in 2011, when she lived in Kazakhstan.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] When academic publisher Elsevier sued Sci-Hub in the US in 2015, Elbakyan wrote a letter to the judge, wherein she explained her motives for starting the project: she could not afford to pay for each of the hundreds of papers she needed for her research project, so she had to pirate them.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She founded her website to help others in the same situation.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In the letter Elbakyan has provided various arguments in support for her cause, such as Elsevier not being an author of papers, and not paying the authors, mentioning that "The general opinion in research community is that research papers should be distributed for free (open access), not sold".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elsevier was granted an injunction against her and $15 million in damages.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Following a lawsuit, Elbakyan remained in hiding due to the risk of extradition.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] There were also lawsuits against Sci-Hub and Elbakyan from other publishers and in other countries.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] On 17 February 2023, a court in India refused to dismiss a blocking application submitted by the legal representatives of the publishers; nonetheless, the legal representatives of Elbakyan are working on a new creative legal strategy, namely the mandatory economic angle.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan is a strong supporter of the open access movement.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her, Sci-Hub is a true implementation of open access principle in science.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She believes that science should be open to all and not behind paywalls.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She has described herself as a devout pirate and thinks that copyright law prevents the free exchange of information online and the free distribution of knowledge on the Internet.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In 2018, she asked supporters of Sci-Hub to join their local Pirate Party in order to fight for copyright laws to be changed.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has stated that she is inspired by communist ideals, and considers the common ownership of ideas to be essential for scientific progress.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In her 2016 interview to *Vox*, she said: "I like the idea of communism, and the idea that knowledge should be common and not intellectual property is very relevant.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] That is especially true for information.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Research articles are used for communication in science.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] But the word 'communication' implies common ownership by itself." She referenced the work of Robert Merton, who considered communism to be a part of scientific ethos.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her, Sci-Hub is fighting for communism in science and against the current state of things when knowledge has become the private property of corporations, because knowledge belongs to everyone.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan does not strictly label herself a Marxist, but adopts much of its propositions.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She wanted to join either the Communist Party of the Russian Federation or Pirate Party of Russia, but was unable to as membership in political parties is restricted to those with Russian citizenship.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] A few months before the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022, when asked in an interview if she was still loyal to Putin, she responded that she is neither aligned with Putin nor with the Russian liberal opposition, reiterating that she identifies herself first and foremost as a communist.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was in conflict with the liberal, pro-Western wing of the Russian scientific community.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] According to her interview, she was attacked on the Internet by 'science popularizers' who supported liberal views that led to the shutdown of Sci-Hub in Russia in 2017 for a few days.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In particular, Elbakyan was strongly critical of the former Dynasty Foundation (shut down in 2015) and its associated figures.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She believes that the foundation was politicized, tied to Russia's liberal opposition, and fit the legal definition of a "foreign agent".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Dynasty's founder, in her opinion, financed researchers whose political views agreed with its own.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan states that after she began to investigate the foundation's activities and published her findings online, she became the target of a cyberharassment campaign by Dynasty's supporters.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In December 2019, *The Washington Post* reported that Elbakyan was under investigation by the US Justice Department for suspected ties to Russia's military intelligence arm — the GRU — to steal U.S. military secrets from defense contractors.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan has denied this, saying that Sci-Hub "...is not in any way directly affiliated with Russian or some other country's intelligence," but noting that "...of course, there could be some indirect help.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] The same as with donations, anyone can send them; they are completely anonymous, so I do not know who exactly is donating to Sci-Hub.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] There could be some help that I'm simply unaware of.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] On May 8, 2021, Elbakyan tweeted that the FBI had served a subpoena to Apple seeking her iCloud data.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] The tweet included a screengrab of the notice from Apple.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] In December 2016, *Nature* named Elbakyan as one of the 10 people who most mattered in science that year.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Some researchers who use Sci-Hub thank Elbakyan in the acknowledgments section of their papers.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] For her actions in creating Sci-Hub, Elbakyan has been called a hero, for example by Nobel laureate Randy Schekman.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] *Ars Technica* has compared her to Aaron Swartz, and *The New York Times* has compared her to Edward Snowden.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Edward Snowden acknowledged Sci-Hub to be one of the most important websites for academics in the world.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] She has also been called a modern-day "Robin Hood", a "Robin Hood of science", and "Science's Pirate Queen".
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Elbakyan was nominated twice for John Maddox Prize and made it to the final shortlist.
[src:diybio-organization/alexandra-elbakyan] Some researchers say that Elbakyan deserves a Nobel Prize for her work.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] The Litter-Free Digital Journal is a project from the South Carolina Aquarium hosted on Anecdata.org with a custom app, that encourages participants to track and remove plastics and other litter from both land and water.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] Users Since the start of the project in 2016, data from more than 7,000 litter cleanups have been entered into the project by more than 1,500 citizen scientists.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] In 2017, a total of 9,746 pieces of trash were logged and 2,333 total litter pieces in 2018.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] However, in 2019 the number of litter pieces recorded grew to 32,600 and in 2020, more than doubled, with 74,977 pieces of trash collected and logged.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] The data from this project has inspired participant activism and has been used to influence public policy in South Carolina, including plastic bag bans.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] The Great Green Crab Hunt project is a citizen science project led by the University of New Hampshire and the New Hampshire Sea Grant and hosted on Anecdata.org.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] The project aims to support scientists and policymakers in finding solutions to the problems caused by the invasive species, European green crabs.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] The project uses a mobile app and participants document the number, shell hardness, sex, and size of crabs seen during one hour.
[src:diybio-organization/anecdata-org] Since the project's inception in 2019, more than 100 observations documenting more than 400 crabs have been added to the project.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive emerged from the **Pirate Library Mirror** (**PiLiMi**) project, an anonymous effort to mirror shadow libraries that completed a full copy of Z-Library in September 2022.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] PiLiMi acknowledged that it "deliberately violated the copyright law in most countries".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The project's initial focus was on preservation rather than on making its data searchable.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Days after US law enforcement seized several Z-Library domains and arrested its alleged operators in November 2022, PiLiMi member Anna (also known as Anna Archivist) launched Anna's Archive, which initially displayed results from Z-Library and LibGen.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has been variously described as a search engine, a metasearch engine, and a shadow library itself.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It operates several mirror sites under different top-level domains.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Its source code is dedicated to the public domain under the CC0 license.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site does not itself host any files (which it claims makes it nonliable for downloads of copyrighted works), but it indexes metadata and links to "third-party" downloads.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It also offers downloads through the IPFS protocol.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site's "source libraries" include LibGen, Sci-Hub, Z-Library, the Internet Archive, DuXiu, MagzDB, Nexus/STC, and HathiTrust; Open Library, WorldCat, and Google Books are listed as metadata-only sources.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Some of these datasets are already publicly accessible, while others are scraped or otherwise privately acquired for distribution.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] They are then released in bulk with torrent files so as to make them resilient to website takedowns.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] As of May 2026, Anna's Archive includes 64,416,225 books and 95,689,473 papers, and its unified list of torrents totals roughly 1.1 petabytes in size.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In March 2025, it averaged over 650,000 daily downloads, roughly 10 times the estimated distribution of the New York Public Library.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive uses a multi-layered server architecture designed for resilience against takedowns and outages.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] According to a 2023 blog post by the site's operators, the backend runs on Flask, MariaDB, and Elasticsearch, hosted on inexpensive servers that are proxied through separate providers to shield the actual hosting infrastructure from legal requests.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Multiple redundant proxy servers and application servers are maintained so that if any single provider terminates service, the site can continue to operate.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site initially used Cloudflare's free tier as an additional caching and DDoS protection layer, taking advantage of Cloudflare's legal position that it acts as a utility rather than a hosting provider and is therefore not directly subject to DMCA takedown requests.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] However, following court orders associated with the Spotify lawsuit in January 2026, Cloudflare disabled its nameservers for several Anna's Archive domains.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] At least some of the site's domains subsequently shifted to DDoS-Guard, a Russian DDoS-protection and content delivery provider.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has registered domains through a variety of registrars across multiple jurisdictions.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Several of its domains, including its `.li` and `.gl` domains, have been registered through Njalla, a privacy-focused domain registration service operated by Njalla SRL in Costa Rica, which registers domains in its own name on behalf of customers to shield their identities.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site's data is standardized under the Anna's Archive Containers (AAC) format, introduced in August 2023 to allow for incremental releases.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Each container consists of metadata and optionally associated binary data.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Metadata files use line-delimited JSON compressed with Zstandard, while binary data files are stored alongside them in structured directories.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The format is designed to be machine-readable, easy to distribute via torrents, and compatible with the site's existing stack of MariaDB, Elasticsearch, and Python.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive describes itself as a nonprofit, claiming that membership fees and donations are mostly spent on server infrastructure and that none are personally used by the site's operators.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It awards memberships and monetary "bounties" to some volunteer contributors.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site operates a tiered download system.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] High-speed downloads on Anna's Archive are only available to users with a paid membership, with the number of fast downloads permitted per 24-hour period varying by membership tier; multiple memberships can be combined additively.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Non-members must use slower options with browser verification to prevent abuse by bots.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] A waitlist-based system allows free users to access somewhat faster servers by limiting the number of concurrent downloads.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive offers high-speed access to its full collection via SFTP to groups training large language models (LLMs) in exchange for large contributions of money or data.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It said it provided such access to about 30 companies (primarily based in China) as of January 2025, including both LLM companies and data brokers.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] DeepSeek's VL model was partly trained on ebook data from the site.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Some lawyers have criticized claims that this constitutes fair use under US copyright law, citing precedent for the importance of market harm.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Because of its legal status, the site states that it cannot accept payments through conventional banking channels directly.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Instead, it relies on cryptocurrency as well as alternative methods such as Amazon gift cards, Cash App and Alipay.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The operators have stated that the need to remain anonymous necessitates avoiding traditional payment processors, and that only a small number of companies support virtual debit cards paid for with cryptocurrency.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive has said its objectives are to "catalog all the books in existence" and "track humanity's progress toward making all these books easily available in digital form".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It has been described as both continuing and greatly extending the ambitions of earlier shadow libraries with its vision of a "universal library" that preserves as many books as possible.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It has been interpreted as part of an ascendant "culture of mistrust towards corporations, institutions, governments, and laws... that perhaps began with the financial collapse of 2008 and the Occupy Wall Street movements" which saw the rise of decentralizing technologies.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna has justified their opposition to copyright on ethical grounds, stating that they "believe that preserving and hosting these files is morally right" and that they and other shadow librarians believe that "information wants to be free".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] They have suggested that copyright law must be reformed as a matter of national security, proposing that Western countries make legal carveouts for text and data mining so as to remain ahead in the AI arms race.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna cites programmer and information activist Aaron Swartz as inspiring the project's collection of metadata.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The site recommends Swartz's writings as well as Stephen Witt's *How Music Got Free* and Michele Boldrin and David K.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Levine's *Against Intellectual Monopoly*, which criticize existing copyright law and have been associated with the copyleft movement.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Since 2023, Anna's Archive domains have appeared in the annual Notorious Markets List of the Office of the United States Trade Representative, which highlights digital and physical markets allegedly involved in large-scale intellectual property infringement.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] These reports describe the site as related to Sci-Hub and LibGen.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In response to a request for comment by the Office on its 2023 List, the Association of American Publishers identified Anna's Archive as an infringing site, and analyzed its cryptocurrency wallets to find that it had received over $29,000 in funds as of July 2023.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In October 2023, Anna's Archive was reported to have scraped the entirety of WorldCat, the world's largest bibliographic database, and made its proprietary data freely available, which Anna described as "a major milestone in mapping out all the books in the world".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] OCLC, WorldCat's maintainer, responded by suing the site in an Ohio federal court in January 2024, claiming the scrape was achieved through cyberattacks on its servers.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It sought over $5 million in total damages and an injunction to stop Anna's Archive from scraping or sharing its data.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] OCLC clarified that although its internal systems were not breached, it believes the site's actions legally constitute hacking.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The only named defendant denied any involvement with the scrape or Anna's Archive.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Technology writer Glyn Moody criticized the suit as "costly and pointless", saying it went against OCLC's stated mission of making information accessible.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In July 2024, in the wake of the suit, the `.org` mirror of Anna's Archive was replaced with a new `.gs` mirror to avoid falling under US jurisdiction; however, soon afterward, the `.gs` domain was suspended and the mirror reverted to the original `.org` domain.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In March 2025, the court deferred judgement on aspects of the case to the Supreme Court of Ohio over concerns about its legal novelty, denying both a motion for default judgement from OCLC and a motion to dismiss from the named defendant.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In April, OCLC reached an agreement with the named defendant to drop her from the case, focusing instead on obtaining judgement against the site itself.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In November, OCLC dropped the demand for damages, focusing its efforts on obtaining an injunction that would compel third-party intermediaries to stop the sharing of the data.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, federal district judge Michael H.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Watson issued a default judgement in favor of OCLC, requiring Anna's Archive to delete the WorldCat data and preventing it from scraping or sharing WorldCat in the future.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive was not expected to comply with the ruling; OCLC stated that it "hopes to take the judgment to website hosting services".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The plaintiffs in the case, a group of authors including Richard Kadrey, Sarah Silverman, and Christopher Golden, alleged that CEO Mark Zuckerberg personally authorized the use of shadow libraries.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The company had argued that its use of copyrighted data in AI training constituted fair use.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In June 2025, the court partially ruled in favor of Meta, finding that the training was "highly transformative" and therefore fair use.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Vince Chhabria, the judge in the case, emphasized that the ruling did not mean that Meta's actions were in fact legitimate, but said that the plaintiffs failed to develop strong arguments.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] He identified "market dilution" as a convincing argument for financial harm not pursued by the plaintiffs — the idea that "by training generative AI models with copyrighted works, companies are creating something that often will dramatically undermine the market for those works".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In December 2025, Anna's Archive reportedly scraped almost 300 terabytes of data from music streaming service Spotify, publishing 256 million rows of track metadata and stating plans to publish 86 million audio files.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] While the audio accounted for only 37% of Spotify's full collection, it represented 99.6% of listens on the platform.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In response, the company stated that it had "identified and disabled the nefarious user accounts that engaged in unlawful scraping".
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Some criticized the release's lack of coverage for less streamed songs.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The metadata release was compared to the open database MusicBrainz, which contains roughly 5 million tracks, around 37 times smaller.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Pro-copyright campaigners predicted that the leaked music would be used to train AI models.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The same month, Spotify, alongside major record labels including Universal Music Group, Sony Music, and Warner Music, filed a lawsuit against the unknown operators of Anna's Archive in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The complaint alleged mass copyright infringement, breach of contract, DMCA violations, and violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, accusing the site of circumventing Spotify's digital rights management systems.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The lawsuit was initially filed under seal "so that Anna's Archive cannot pre-emptively frustrate" countermeasures they seek.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, the court granted a temporary restraining order, followed by a preliminary injunction issued on January 16 by US District Court Judge Jed Rakoff.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The injunction ordered Anna's Archive to cease hosting, linking to, or distributing the copyrighted works, and also targeted third-party intermediaries including domain registries, hosting companies, and Cloudflare.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] As a result, several Anna's Archive domain names were suspended, including the `.org` domain overseen by the Public Interest Registry and the `.se` domain.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive initially believed that the suspension was unrelated to their activities.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In response to a March 2024 lawsuit accusing Nvidia of training LLMs on data from a shadow library the company disputed the characterization of Anna's Archive and other repositories as "shadow libraries", despite Anna's own use of the term.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In January 2026, additional evidence was presented in the case suggesting that Nvidia also directly contacted Anna's Archive in order to gain high-speed access to its data.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive denied ever dealing with Nvidia directly, and raised the possibility that Nvidia used an intermediary party to avoid legal issues.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] On January 29, 2026, Nvidia filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Following a lawsuit brought in March 2026 by a group of 13 publishers, on 19 May 2026, U.S.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] District Court for the Southern District of New York issued a default judgment ordering the website to immediately cease copying and distributing millions of files that it had illegally downloaded.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The publishers were awarded a $19.5 million default judgment, and the judge ordered a global domain takedown.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In January 2024, Italy's national communications agency ordered major internet service providers (ISPs) in the country to block Anna's Archive due to a copyright complaint by the Italian Publishers Association.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] An investigation by the Digital Services Directorate confirmed the presence of copyrighted works on the site and found that some of its servers were likely owned by a Ukrainian hosting provider, but failed to uncover the identity of its operators.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In March 2024, the Rotterdam District Court ordered major ISPs in the Netherlands to block Anna's Archive and LibGen due to a request by advocacy group BREIN.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The order was "dynamic", meaning that if the blocked sites changed domains or IP addresses in the future, ISPs would be obligated to update their blocks.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In December 2024, the UK Publishers Association won an order from the High Court of Justice requiring major ISPs to block Anna's Archive and other copyright-infringing sites, extending a list of sites blocked since 2015 under section 97A of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The Association said it identified over one million records of copyrighted books and journal articles on Anna's Archive domains.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The judge ordered FPS Economy's anti-piracy service to block the sites in the interim.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In the event of noncompliance, the sites face fines of up to 500,000 euros.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] On October 11, 2025, TorrentFreak reported that major ISPs in Germany had blocked access to the main domains of Anna's Archive.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The blockade was initiated by the Clearing Body for Copyright on the Internet (CUII), a coalition of rightsholders and ISPs that coordinates voluntary site blocking measures.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Anna's Archive was among Google Search's ten most reported domains for DMCA takedown by June 2024.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] By November 2025, Google had removed 749 million Anna's Archive URLs from its search results, representing 5 percent of all takedown requests sent to the search engine since 2012.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] These requests came from over 1,000 authors and publishers.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] It has been one of the most targeted sites of Dutch anti-piracy service Link-Busters, which sends takedown requests to Google and other search engines on behalf of major publishers.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] In January 2025, the messaging app Telegram suspended the Anna's Archive channel for copyright infringement, despite the operators reportedly taking precautions to avoid infringing posts on the app.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] Z-Library's Telegram channel was suspended the same week, and neither was alerted of the action.
[src:diybio-organization/anna-s-archive] The removals were speculated to be linked to legal action by the Delhi High Court.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The **Australian Citizen Science Association** (ACSA) is a membership-based organisation that promotes public participation in science and research projects in Australia and internationally.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The organisation provides a range of knowledge sharing, networking, professional development, advocacy and promotional opportunities for members and the community to participate in citizen science.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association operates nationally as well as through five state-based chapters.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] ACSA is an incorporated association registered with the Australian Charities and Not-for-profits Commission in 2018.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association supports a range of activities including a national conference held every two years, workshops and training, bioblitz campaigns, a small grants program, public outreach and education, and collaboration with national and international organisations.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association has a memorandum of understanding with other citizen science organisations including the US Citizen Science Association, the European Citizen Science Association, Citizen Science Asia and CitSci Africa Association.
[src:diybio-organization/australian-citizen-science-association] The ACSA is a member of the Citizen Science Global Partnership.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] The website provides resources for those in the do-it-yourself biology community.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] It maintains a directory of local groups encompassing both meetup groups and organizations maintaining community laboratory space, and a weekly blog listing events hosted by these organizations.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] The website also hosts safety information including ethics codes developed by the community and an "ask a biosafety professional" feature, as well as DIY instructions for making several types of laboratory equipment.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] The work 'A Biopunk Manifesto' delivered by Patterson at the UCLA conference lays down the principles of the biopunk movement, in an homage to the prior work of cypherpunk Eric Hughes.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] That a significant proportion of the DIYbio mailing list membership are openly in support of outsourcing DNA synthesis and sequencing makes it difficult to determine whether this definition truly applies; in general, the two hobbies are impossible to distinguish and share a common community.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] As DIYbio has grown, tools and materials have become available including instructions on how to build lab equipment and DIYbio stores like The ODIN that provide inexpensive materials.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] Some participants call themselves ‘biohackers’, not hackers in the sense of infiltrating protected places and stealing information, but hackers in the original sense of taking things apart and putting them back together in a new, better way.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] These biohackers often pursue these interests outside of their jobs, companies or institutional labs.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] Beginning in 2009 the FBI engaged active members of the DIYbio Google Groups mailing list much like they engage scientific boards at universities and businesses.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] The dialogue focused on safety issues and aimed to instill a sense of self-policing in the ad-hoc online community.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] Because DIYbio and biohacking takes place on an international level, the FBI is limited in its ability to monitor and investigate all activity.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] However, in 2012 the FBI held a DIYbio conference in Walnut Creek, California where they paid to fly in biohackers from all over the world in an attempt to forge a connection to the DIYbio community.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] DIYbio was featured at a table in Newcastle Maker Faire in March, 2010, with DNA extraction experiments and projects involving isolation of luminescent bacteria being demonstrated or given away.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] The "Dremelfuge", an open-source, 3D printed Dremel-powered centrifuge, was presented as an example of how Biotech can be made more accessible.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] A presentation on the potential of DIYbio and synthetic biology gathered a sizeable attendance.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] Internal discussions and proposed projects for DIYbio members often include discussion of risk mitigation and public perception.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] An oft-discussed topic is the search for a convenient and safe "model organism" for DIYbio which would evoke less suspicion than E.coli.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] Suggestions include *Janthinobacterium lividum*, *Bacillus subtilis*, *Acetobacteria* or *Gluconacetobacter spp.*, and baker's yeast.
[src:diybio-organization/diybio-organization] A list of potential biosafe organisms was drawn up by the National Center for Biotechnology Education.
